			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">From the new NSF export available in Deflemask, it looks like Delek found a very interesting technique for doing PCM in NSF. I hope he doesn't mind me sharing. It's not open source, but it's pretty easy to deduce from a debugger:<br /><br />During INIT:<br />1. SEI<br />2. Write $00 to $4017<br /><br />Non returning PLAY:<br />1. SEI<br />2. PCM playback loop with a poll of $4015 after every loop.<br />3. If $4015 bit 6 is set, do your regular music update, then return to loop.<br /><br /><br />I was surprised to find that many NSF players, including the PowerPak, support this. There are a number of players, however, which do not really support this feature of the frame counter (NSFPlay included, though I've been meaning to rewrite its frame counter).<br /><br />Anyhow, this is pretty interesting. It seems a lot more viable than the non-returning INIT hack supported by foo_gep. Obviously it's got a few support problems (use of SEI is bit of a red flag to me), but I thought it was pretty cool that it works with a lot of NSF player implementations. Also, from what I remember reading, $4015 will fail to clear bit 6 if you read on the same cycle it's set? Maybe you'll get a double frame now and then.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

						<table width="100%" cellspacing="0">
						<tr valign="middle">
