						<div class="postbody">Here's a clip of multi-expansion being done live on hardware:<br /><br /><a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zLCmxKZ2-o4" class="postlink">Part 1</a><br /><a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=A_m816HUjpQ" class="postlink">Part 2</a><br /><br />The DJ in the video is actually Robokabuto himself. What's more, he used a YMZ-294 instead of a Sunsoft 5B. :p<br /><br />But that's besides the point here. As tokumaru pointed out, basically I treat the NES/Famicom as I would any other synthesizer, really. I don't really care about using my NSFs in games or tech demos; all I'm interested in is making music that pushes a system to its very limit. In my opinion, PCM falls under that description, regardless of whether it's feasible in a game context or not. I think this 'hack' Delek found would be pretty neat, if not for the fact that it's incompatible with most NSF players (including NSFPlay). I haven't tested it on my TNS-HFC3 yet, but I'd wager that it doesn't work, despite reports that it does the Power Pak.</div>

